    <h1 id="overview">Above the NOI line adjustments</h1>
    <h2>How to calculate the Adjusted NOI</h2>
    <br>
    <p>
      Often the NOI around the End Date isn’t a fair representation of NOI that
      would be expected in most time periods. To calculate the adjusted NOI
      (NOI<sub>Adj</sub>), there are two types of adjustments that may need to
      be done–Gross Up Occupancy Adjustments and NOI Adjustments.
    </p>
    <p>
      Both types of adjustments are subtracted from the NOI to determine the
      NOI<sub>Adj</sub>
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Gross Up Occupancy Adjustment</h3>
    <p>
      A common issue with using the NOI without any adjustments is that the
      occupancy levels based on the End Date may be higher or lower than
      historical norms. To account for this, valuers often use an adjustment
      called a Gross Up Occupancy Adjustment.
    </p>
    <p>
      The formula for calculating NOI<sub>Adj</sub> is:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
        <math>
          <msub>
            <mi>NOI</mi>
            <mi>Adj</mi>
          </msub>
          <mpadded lspace="0.3em" width="2em">
            <mo>=</mo>
          </mpadded>
          <mi>NOI</mi>
          <mpadded lspace="0.3em" width="2em">
            <mo>×</mo>
          </mpadded>
          <mfrac>
            <mpadded height="1.2em" voffset="0.2em">
              <mi>Gross Up %</mi>
            </mpadded>
            <mpadded height="1.1em">
              <mrow>
                <msub>
                  <mi>Avg. Occupancy</mi>
                  <mi>End Period</mi>
                </msub>
                <mi>%</mi>
              </mrow>
            </mpadded>
          </mfrac>
        </math>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <p>Where:</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-8 text-gray-800 text-base pb-4 leading-8">
      <li>NOI is the unadjusted NOI in the period that is being capitalized</li>
      <li>Gross Up % is the typical occupancy for the property</li>
      <li>Avg. Occupancy<sub>End Period</sub> % is the average occupancy rate for the period being capitalized</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This formula can be rearranged to find the Gross Up Adjustment that
      should be applied to the NOI:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
        <math>
          <mi>Gross Up Adjustment</mi>
          <mpadded lspace="0.3em" width="2em">
            <mo>=</mo>
          </mpadded>
          <mi>NOI</mi>
          <mpadded lspace="0.3em" width="2em">
            <mo>×</mo>
          </mpadded>
          <mfrac>
            <mpadded height="1.2em" voffset="0.2em">
              <mi>Gross Up %</mi>
            </mpadded>
            <mpadded height="1.1em">
              <mrow>
                <msub>
                  <mi>Avg. Occupancy</mi>
                  <mi>End Period</mi>
                </msub>
                <mi>%</mi>
              </mrow>
            </mpadded>
          </mfrac>
          <mpadded lspace="0.7em" width="2.4em">
            <mo>-</mo>
          </mpadded>
          <mi>NOI</mi>
        </math>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Note: the Gross Up Adjustment to NOI can be either positive (the
      occupancy level at the period around the End Date is lower than normal)
      or negative (the occupancy level at the period around the End Date is
      higher than normal).
    </p>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Example</h3>
    <p>
      We are modeling the Reversionary Value of a property for a landlord and
      have decided to use the Forward 12-Months method. What is the Gross Up
      Adjustment if the property NOI is $250,000 but the average occupancy
      during that period was 80% while the typical occupancy was 90%?
    </p>
    <p>
      The normalized occupancy would be <b>$281,250</b> ($100,000 x 90% / 80%).
      Therefore the <b>Gross Up Occupancy Adjustment would be $31,250</b>
      ($281,250 - $250,000).
    </p>
    <figure>
      <figcaption>[Insert ReturnSuite GIF]</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <div class="border border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm p-6 pb-4 mx-6 my-4">
      <div class="flex gap-0.5">
        <a href="{{ url_for('get_index') }}" title="ReturnSuite">
