      </p>
    </div>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Operational Adjustments</h3>
    <p>
      Operational Adjustments are modifications made to the NOI to provide a
      more accurate forecast of a property's typical financial performance.
      These adjustments account for unusual or non-recurring operating items
      which distort the NOI.
    </p>
    <p>
      By normalizing the NOI, these adjustments ensure that the Reversionary
      Value calculation is based on a realistic and sustainable income stream,
      rather than temporary or anomalous conditions. This is important since
      the NOI will be capitalized like a Perpetuity which is based on the
      assumption that the property will produce a steady stream of income
      far into the future.
    </p>
    <p>
      Operational Adjustments can be either positive or negative, depending on
      whether they increase or decrease the expected typical NOI.
    </p>
    <p>
      ReturnSuite offers two options for Operational Adjustments:
    </p>
    <ol class="list-decimal pl-8 text-gray-800 text-base pb-2 leading-8">
      <li><b>Amount</b> - a fixed dollar amount, or</li>
      <li><b>Percentage of NOI</b> - a variable amount which is a percentage of the unadjusted NOI</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="border border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm p-6 pb-4 mx-6 my-4">
      <div class="flex gap-0.5">
        <a href="{{ url_for('get_index') }}" title="ReturnSuite">
          <img class="h-12 w-auto" src="{{ url_for('img', path='/returnsuite-logo.svg') }}" alt="ReturnSuite logo" width="360px" height="85px">
        </a>
        <span class="font-medium text-gray-800">TIPS</span>
      </div>
      <p class="font-medium">
        When entering Operational Adjustments, keep in mind which NOI period
        you decided to capitalize.
      </p>
      <p class="font-medium">
        For example if you want to make an adjustment of positive $25,000
        adjustment to NOI because of an extraordinary cost in the final year of
        the Analysis Period but you will be capitalizing the NOI 12 months
        after the End Date, the adjustment won’t be needed.
      </p>
    </div>
    <hr class="mt-2 mb-6 border-gray-300">
    <h3>Example</h3>
    <p>
      Continuing with our previous example, the landlord had previously taken
      advantage of a property tax abatement program offered in their
      municipality. The program resulted in a $10,000 savings to property
      taxes which will extend beyond the End Date of the Analysis Period, but
      expires shortly afterwards. How would this adjustment affect the
      NOI<sub>Adj</sub>?
    </p>
    <figure>
      <figcaption>[Insert ReturnSuite GIF]</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The NOI will need to adjust downwards by $10,000 to account for the
      expected change in NOI shortly after the End Date.
    </p>
    <p>
      This would result in a <b>NOI<sub>Adj</sub> of $271,250</b>
      ($250,000 + $31,250 - $10,000).
    </p>
